orth, that one most often only knew from hearsay and which were inhabited by strange beings: humans with their faces on their chest, without a mouth, or with dog heads. On the other hand, the edges of one's world could just mean the borders of the community where one lived and that one sometimes might not have had the possibility to cross during one's whole life.In this volume specialists from eight European countries offer their ideas about different edges of the medieval world and contribute to a discussion that has been increasing greatly in Medieval Studies in recent times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCivilization, MedievalvCongresses. 0aCivilization, MedievalxCongresses. 0aMiddle AgesvCongresses. 0aMiddle AgesxCongresses. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBaltic Countries, Civilization, Medieval, Middle Ages.1 aDoležalová, Lucie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaritz, Gerhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaritz, Gerhard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJørgensen, Torstein, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKreem, Juhan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKreem, Juhan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMundal, Else, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPettitt, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPluskowski, Aleksander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmieder, Felicitas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSebő, Judit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSelart, Anti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1